snippet.textDisplay: It could might as well have nothing to do with late 80s romantcism, or have to do with a bit of both. Music can create a nostalgic mood without the listener actually being nostalgic to the particular piece, that's not stranger than achieving other emotions through music. The track come across as having a sense of wonder, pensiveness (particulary at the beginning) and playfulness so I'm not surprised at the whole nostalgia-angle.

snippet.textDisplay: Kinuyo Yamashita. Konami, Castlevania. And I dare you to call her a "chiptune artist/musician" after looking at her youtube page. Most of these people were musicians. There was no such thing as "chiptune music" as something someone would just do and play for an audience back then. Most of these people were music students/graduates/talents just getting work. The styles of the music were limited/dictated by the limitations of the console hardware.
snippet.textOriginal: Kinuyo Yamashita. Konami, Castlevania. And I dare you to call her a "chiptune artist/musician" after looking at her youtube page. Most of these people were musicians. snippet.textDisplay: I was making a general statement, not to this game in particular. The gaming market crashed in 1983, and consisted until NES was released in 1985, and it came with a very large game library. But video games really picked up in the 1990's starting in 1992. Even at that point arcades still made a larger profit than home systems at that point. So as I said, the people that created this amazing game had no idea how many would see it, but put effort into anyway. Calm down.

snippet.textDisplay:
The NES was very popular, I'm not doubting that, but it was considered a kid's toy. Adults didn't tend to play it, or even know about it, unless they had families who were also interested in it. 

Back then, the only TV commercials you would see for games were during cartoons. Nowadays, video game ads are played during primetime and during trailers at movies.

Video game fans have undergone a massive demographic change and expansion over the years. You cannot deny that.

snippet.textDisplay:
The NES era was my era, and I remember it a bit differently. It was big, but to a different kind of audience. My parents and teachers had no idea what a video game console even was, they just knew that the NES was all the rage among kids and is what they all wanted for Christmas.

Nowadays, video games are inescapable and embedded into our culture, even to those who don't play them, and are generally accepted as an art medium along with books and movies. When I was a kid, it wasn't like that.

snippet.textDisplay:
Sometimes I wonder whether or not the composers of NES tunes had any idea that, in twenty years, people would still be listening to their work and holding it in their hearts as a beloved, timeless classic.

For all we know, it was something they might have thrown together in a few hours for a licensed game on a then-obscure medium of entertainment that they figured only a handful of children would ever hear.

Sometimes the most touching art can come from the unlikeliest of places.

@Blaquecell
You're not the only one, and there's more to it than that.

All the music and sound effects in MM2 was done by Takeshi Tateishi and Sakaguchi deconfirmed Ducktales as being his.

In other words, the same person responsible for MM2's soundtrack was also responsible for that of DuckTalkes'.  Bet you didn't think it was that simple, huh?

I think a lot of starting gamers look upon their parents and older friends and hear about their memories and they want those memories as well. They feel like they can't have that without all of this "Epic everything". They misinterpret why those old school gaming memories are there, only seeing how big the memories themselves are.

snippet.textDisplay:
Game music doesn't serve the same purpose today as it did back in the day. Back in the days the song had to be catchy and awesome to fill the void left by lacking sound effects. In games now, due to increased memory and computing ability, everything can be made to make noise, reducing the role of music. That's why most game music today isn't as good.

However, there are exceptions. Nintendo and ZUN (maker of Touhou) first come to mind, but are by no means the only decent musicians of today.

snippet.textDisplay:
@GustavElun hey there, maybe someone already told you but anyway. to loop you have to modify the video url with commands for fullscreen (/v/) , loop and autoplay.
The video url for this very video would look like this:

...youtube.com/v/G_80PQ543rM&loop=1&autoplay=1

So instead of " /watch?v= " you fill in " /v/ " and don't forget " & " as command separators.
it have to be on fullscreen or it will not work

snippet.textDisplay: @Makatacaly Most RPG's and platformers actually still have awesome music.  FPS games make silence to enhance the atmosphere.  I recommend Tales of Symphonia and the Super Mario Galaxy games for those that wish they were born in the early 90s or late 80s.  They are quite solid gameplay and musical experiences that I dare say are just as good as Ducktales.  I grew up with my older sister who loved the show and would watch it all the time.  I also had the game.

Ah the days of striving to accomplish something in video games. I tried so hard as a kid to beat this at a friends house, we would sit around and trade off on parts we were good at and still lose. When we did beat it late one night past bed time we yelled so loud we got in trouble.

Makes me sad to think how, today, every game you play you save your progress after every step or you have to spend 20+ hours to unlock the fun.

G1Sidesmash: "This tune stands out in my mind as the theme of the 8-bit era. When you listen, you hear a small tune, like the leftovers from the video game crash of '83. It gains momentum with more tunes, and then explodes, just like the popularity of the NES in '89."

snippet.textDisplay:
It's by Yoshihiro Sakaguchi, who also wrote music for Mega Man 1 and Mega Man 2.  Most of the Mega Man (Rockman) games had more than one composer.  I know that he wrote the music for HeatMan in Mega Man 2, but I don't know specifically what other pieces he contributed for those games.

Anyway, he's clearly, a composer with a real talent for melody!!  I'd love to know what he's up to now, and hear some more of his work if he's got anything newer.
snippet.textOriginal:
It's by Yoshihiro Sakaguchi, who also wrote music for Mega Man 1 and Mega Man 2.  Most of the Mega Man (Rockman) games had more than one composer.  I know that he wrote the music for HeatMan in Mega Man 2, but I don't know specifically what other pieces he contributed for those games.

Anyway, he's clearly, a composer with a real talent for melody!!  I'd love to know what he's up to now, and hear some more of his work if he's got anything newer.
